### CSS Grid Areas

**grid-template-areas** creates named areas for visual layout structure.

---

### Define Areas

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-areas:
    "header header header"
    "nav    main   aside"
    "footer footer footer";
}
```

Each string = one row. Each word = one column cell.

---

### Assign Items to Areas

```css
header { grid-area: header; }
nav { grid-area: nav; }
main { grid-area: main; }
aside { grid-area: aside; }
footer { grid-area: footer; }
```

---

### Empty Cells with Dot

```css
.container {
  grid-template-areas:
    "header header header"
    ".      main   aside"    /* Dot = empty cell */
    "footer footer footer";
}
```

Use `.` for cells you want to leave empty.

---

### Responsive Areas

```css
/* Mobile: single column */
@media (max-width: 600px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-areas:
      "header"
      "nav"
      "main"
      "aside"
      "footer";
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
  }
}

/* Desktop: sidebar + main */
@media (min-width: 601px) {
  .container {
    grid-template-areas:
      "header header"
      "nav    main"
      "aside  main"
      "footer footer";
    grid-template-columns: 200px 1fr;
  }
}
```

---

### Key Rules

- Each area name represents a **rectangle**
- Area must form a **contiguous rectangle** (no L-shapes)
- Same name = merged cells
- `.` = empty cell
- All rows must have same number of columns

---

### Invalid Examples

```css
/* INVALID - L-shape not allowed */
grid-template-areas:
  "a a b"
  "a c b";  /* 'a' is L-shaped */

/* INVALID - inconsistent columns */
grid-template-areas:
  "a b"
  "c d e";  /* Row 1 has 2 cols, row 2 has 3 */
```

---

> **Best Practice:** Use `grid-template-areas` for page-level layouts. It makes the visual structure immediately readable.
